5
00:00:21,140 --> 00:00:25,490
Higher education is a great way to equip yourself with some core skills

6
00:00:25,700 --> 00:00:30,430
but it will not prepare you for actual challenges your face with client's work

7
00:00:31,210 --> 00:00:32,250
In other words

8
00:00:32,580 --> 00:00:39,270
being proficient with a design tool and a few methods doesn't make you a user experience designer

9
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:43,280
There simply isn't a 1 size fits all process

10
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,600
Being effective requires adaptability

11
00:00:47,230 --> 00:00:49,680
something you don't really learn in school

12
00:00:50,070 --> 00:00:53,330
much less in a sixth month training camp

13
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,950
It's gained through experience on the job and learning what's appropriate given the needs of the project

14
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:12,450
I found my way to user experience through graphic design and slowly over many different roles and experiences that led me to become a user experience designer

15
00:01:13,380 --> 00:01:21,160
It took time and commitment to continue to pursue roles within teams that I knew could teach and challenge me

16
00:01:21,730 --> 00:01:24,900
That's not to say that I think my path is the only one

17
00:01:25,620 --> 00:01:26,620
but once again

18
00:01:26,690 --> 00:01:29,390
nothing can substitute real world experience

19
00:01:30,220 --> 00:01:39,310
You can start anywhere as long as you know your end goal and you commit to actively pursuing opportunities to learn and grow along the way
